  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my neighbors. Growing up in Bologna with a father who had a PhD and a mother who only went to primary school taught me early on that education isn't always a straight line. I remember my brother, who's now a software engineer, telling me how his high school math teacher once said, 'You're not cut out for this,' because he was the only one in class who didn't speak English fluently. That moment stuck with him, and it's a microcosm of what stereotype threat really means: the anxiety that comes from knowing you're part of a group that's been stereotyped as less capable in a particular field. In STEM, this can be especially damaging because the field is often seen as 'for the smart ones,' and when someone feels like they don't fit that mold, their performance can suffer. I think we absolutely need to address it. As someone who's spent years on the road delivering packages across Italy, I've seen how people's confidence can evaporate under pressure—just like how students might feel when they're in a classroom where everyone else seems to have it figured out. The solution isn't just about changing the system but about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. For me, it's about small, consistent actions: mentoring programs that pair students with someone who's been through similar struggles, or simply encouraging people to talk about their fears without judgment. In a city like Bologna, where there's a strong sense of community, we can build bridges instead of walls. It's not about fixing people—it's about fixing the environment so that everyone has a chance to thrive.",
